Physical Habitat

Physical habitat includes in-channel morphology, channel form, connectivity with a river’s riparian zone and wider landscape. The Water Framework Directive focuses on these elements under the banner of “morphology”.

1 Morphology related RNAGs

Due to the design of the Water Framework Directive, morphology is very rarely an RNAG, a better representation of where morphological pressure acts within a catchment is shown in the map below: where morphology is a Significant Water Management Issue (SWMI), in layman’s terms a SWMI is the pressure which we think puts our ability to achieve WFD at most risk.

Morphology specific RNAGs within Avon Bristol Urban are as follows:

[1] "The Avon Bristol Urban doesn't have any morphology RNAGs, the morphology of its waterbodies' therefore 'Supports Good'. In this context, 'Supports Good' merely means these waterbodies are not considered to have pristine morphology."

1.1 Waterbodies with Physical Modification as their Significant Waterbody Management Issue

The below map shows waterbodies in the Avon Bristol Urban which have morphology as their SWMI. More granular, reach-level data on morphology can be viewed by clicking the River Habitat Survey (RHS) box in the top right.

The median RHS Habitat Quality Assessment Score in Wessex is 42, in the Avon Bristol Urban, the median RHS HQA is 36. Low scores often indicate channelisation, whilst high scores indicate a more natural physical habitat.
